<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-688-966  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 688 966.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Federal Computer Week  August 7 1989 v3 n32 p7(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Agency security plans fall short of mark, officials say.andO;(including representatives from the Office of Management andBudget's Office of Information and Regulatory Affairs, theNational Institute of Standards and Technology and the NationalSecurity Agency)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Levine, Arnold S.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Federal officials overseeing computer security planning to complywith the 1987 Computer Security Act find a number of problems inthe responses of government agencies.andP;  The act states thatagencies must develop detailed security plans for each system thatprocesses sensitive information.andP;  These plans must be submitted tothe National Institute of Standards and Technology (NIST), theOffice of Management and Budget's Office of Information andRegulatory Affairs and the National Security Agency.andP;  Typicalproblems in the 550 responses reviewed to this point were afailure to explain why computer systems required protection, theoveraggregation of computer systems into plans and the absence ofan overall understanding of agency policy context.andP;  Options underreview include having NIST and NSA officials conduct on-sitereviews of agency plans.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Statute:   Computer Security Act of 1987 (interpretation and construction).andO;Topic:     United States. National Institute of Standards and TechnologyUnited States. National Security AgencyUnited States. Office of Management and Budget. Office ofInformation and Regulatory AffairsGovernment AgencySecurityGovernment Regulation.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>